The expedition referred to in v. 29 f. was undertaken by Augustus in 27 B.e., when, according to Dio C. 53, 22, ἐξώρμησε μὲν ὡς καὶ ἐς τὴν Βριττανῖαν στρατεύσων, ἐς δὲ δὴ τὰς Γαλατίας ἐλθὼν ἐνταῦθα διέτριψεν. The following year he again laid plans for the invasion, but was kept back by an uprising in Spain. In this year, too, preparations were being made for the expedition of Aelius Gallus against the Arabians to which vv. 30-32 refer (cf. ode 29 of this book). 26 B.c. is therefore the most probable date of the ode. O diva, gratum quae regis Antium, praesens vel imo tollere de gradu mortale corpus vel superbos vertere funeribus triumphos:

5 te pauper ambit sollicita prece ruris colonus, te dominam aequoris

x. diva: F ortune‚ the goddess who rules at will the vicissitudes of life, is here identified with the Fortunae Antiates, whose temple at Antium was a famous shrine until late times. With this shrine was associated a popular oracle, therefore the goddesses were called by Mart. 5, 1, 3 veridicaesorores.
